      "user_id" : 2523147,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 38,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/ogeU4.gif?s=256",
      "display_name" : "prime",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2523147/prime"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 21,
    "last_activity_date" : 1528794853,
    "last_edit_date" : 1528794853,
    "creation_date" : 1520847482,
    "answer_id" : 49232011,
    "question_id" : 27454025,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If the date String does not include any value for hours, minutes and etc you cannot directly convert this to a <code>LocalDateTime</code>. You can only convert it to a <code>LocalDate</code>, because the string <strong>only</strong> <strong>represent</strong> the <strong>year,month and date</strong> components it would be the correct thing to do.</p>\n\n<pre><code>DateTimeFormatter dtf = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(\"yyyyMMdd\");\nLocalDate ld = LocalDate.parse(\"20180306\", dtf); // 2018-03-06\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Anyway you can convert this to <code>LocalDateTime</code>.</p>\n\n<pre><code>DateTimeFormatter dtf = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(\"yyyyMMdd\");\nLocalDate ld = LocalDate.parse(\"20180306\", dtf);\nLocalDateTime ldt = LocalDateTime.of(ld, LocalTime.of(0,0)); // 2018-03-06T00:00\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1379686,
      "reputation" : 2355,
      "user_id" : 1312971,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/ogYYP.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "mawburn",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1312971/mawburn"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 50,
    "last_activity_date" : 1527022176,
    "last_edit_date" : 1527022176,
    "creation_date" : 1526584711,
    "answer_id" : 50399049,
    "question_id" : 27454025,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>For anyone who landed here with this error, like I did:</p>\n\n<p><code>Unable to obtain LocalDateTime from TemporalAccessor: {HourOfAmPm=0, MinuteOfHour=0}</code></p>\n\n<p>It came from a the following line: </p>\n\n<pre><code>LocalDateTime.parse(date, DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(\"M/d/yy h:mm\"));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It turned out that it was because I was using a 12hr Hour pattern on a 0 hour, instead of a 24hr pattern. </p>\n\n<p>Changing the hour to 24hr pattern by using a capital H fixes it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>LocalDateTime.parse(date, DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(\"M/d/yy H:mm\"));\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14705923,
      "reputation" : 7,
      "user_id" : 10620654,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fb926af02e8cf3d76d1dcc399b16fdf3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Vinay Kasarla",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10620654/vinay-kasarla"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1541633108,
    "last_edit_date" : 1541633108,
    "creation_date" : 1541624990,
    "answer_id" : 53197854,
    "question_id" : 27454025,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Try this one:</p>\n\n<pre><code>DateTimeFormatter dateTimeFormatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(\"MM-dd-yyyy\"); \nLocalDate fromLocalDate = LocalDate.parse(fromdstrong textate, dateTimeFormatter);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You can add any format you want. That works for me!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6187514,
      "reputation" : 9034,
      "user_id" : 6872018,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 33,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0092ab9e1d482fcc98679e2c4ba6cba9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Jeff Cook",
